{"Body": "<p><span style=\"font-family: Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif; font-size: 12px;\">\n</span></p><p>A series of documents that the Students' Union handed over to various college authorities earlier have been released.</p>\n<p>The following letter was addressed to the Provost, Dr. John Hegerty:</p>\n<p><em>Dear Provost,</em></p>\n<p><em>The Students&rsquo; Union is occupying the library in protest at the cuts made to library services. We wish to stress that this demonstration is a result of the frustration felt by students towards the inaction of the College authorities.</em></p>\n<p><em>The College has refused to accept the importance of adequate open hours and access to materials. This has been pointed out to the College on numerous occasions by the Students&rsquo; &nbsp;Union, however we have seen no demonstrable change to the problems.</em></p>\n<p><em>The Students&rsquo; Union feels that this situation is unsustainable and has directly caused this action today and unless our demands are met we will occupy the library for twenty-four hours. Furthermore, we are prepared to intensify our campaign at local and national level until there is a satisfactory resolution for the students in a timely manner.&nbsp;</em></p>\n<p><em>Our specific demands are:</em></p>\n<p><em>The library to be open on Sundays; Sunday opening hours become a core service offered by the library and regularise it as a standard year-long service.</em></p>\n<p><em>Any cut made to the book budget be reversed and the Students&rsquo; Union be explicitly consulted before any changes to the book budget in future.</em></p>\n<p><em>The library bring its opening hours and service hours in line with the national average to be agreed between the Students&rsquo; Union and the library.</em></p>\n<p><em>No further cuts in opening hours or service hours without consultation with the Students&rsquo; Union.</em></p>\n<p><em>The College and the library work together to ensure that the library has adequate resources including necessary funding to carry out these demands.</em></p>\n<p><em>We will be in the library when you are ready to discuss this.&nbsp;</em></p>\n<p><em>Trinity College Students&rsquo; Union</em></p>\n<p><em><br /></em></p>\n<p>The following letter was handed to various members of the library staff as the sit in began:</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em>Dear Library Staff,&nbsp;</em></p>\n<p><em>To protest library cut backs in library services Trinity College Students&rsquo; Union has organized a sit in for twenty-four hours beginning at close of services today.</em></p>\n<p><em>The Students&rsquo; Union wants to make it clear that it has no issue with the library staff and the great work that they do.</em></p>\n<p><em>We would kindly ask that you quickly gather your belongings and make your way towards the exit.</em></p>\n<p><em>We appreciate your cooperation.&nbsp;</em></p>\n<p><em>Trinity Students&rsquo; Union</em></p>\n<p><em><br /></em></p>\n<p>The following letter was addressed to the Junior Dean, Dr. Emma Stokes:</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-IE\"><em>Dear Junior Dean,</em></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-IE\"><em>The Students&rsquo; Union is occupying the library in protest at the cuts made to library services. We wish to stress that this demonstration is a result of the frustration felt by students towards the inaction of the College authorities.</em></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-IE\"><em>The students who are engaged in the sit in are exercising their right to a democratic and peaceful protest. The Students&rsquo; Union will support each and every student who is exercising their rights in a peaceful manner.</em></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-IE\"><em>We trust that you will respect their rights.</em></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-IE\"><em>Thank you,&nbsp;</em></span></p>\n<p class=\"MsoNormal\"><span lang=\"EN-IE\"><em>Trinity College Students&rsquo; Union</em></span></p>\n", "Imageurl": "<p><span style=\"font-family: Verdana, Geneva, sans-serif; font-size: 12px;\">\n</span></p><p>A series of documents that the Students' Union handed over to various college authorities earlier have been released.</p>\n<p>The following letter was addressed to the Provost, Dr. John Hegerty:</p>\n<p><em>Dear Provost,</em></p>\n<p><em>The Students&rsquo; Union is occupying the library in protest at the cuts made to library services. We wish to stress that this demonstration is a result of the frustration felt by students towards the inaction of the College authorities.</em></p>\n<p><em>The College has refused to accept the importance of adequate open hours and access to materials. This has been pointed out to the College on numerous occasions by the Students&rsquo; &nbsp;Union, however we have seen no demonstrable change to the problems.</em></p>\n<p><em>The Students&rsquo; Union feels that this situation is unsustainable and has directly caused this action today and unless our demands are met we will occupy the library for twenty-four hours. Furthermore, we are prepared to intensify our campaign at local and national level until there is a satisfactory resolution for the students in a timely manner.&nbsp;</em></p>\n<p><em>Our specific demands are:</em></p>\n<p><em>The library to be open on Sundays; Sunday opening hours become a core service offered by the library and regularise it as a standard year-long service.</em></p>\n<p><em>Any cut made to the book budget be reversed and the Students&rsquo; Union be explicitly consulted before any changes to the book budget in future.</em></p>\n<p><em>The library bring its opening hours and service hours in line with the national average to be agreed between the Students&rsquo; Union and the library.</em></p>\n<p><em>No further cuts in opening hours or service hours without consultation with the Students&rsquo; Union.</em></p>\n<p><em>The College and the library work together to ensure t